@JordynAlger I say "medium". I currently have 3, but I personally set the threshold for "a lot" at like 7 or 8. 😆
@ErinFulmer That is wild! Now I have a new rabbit hole to go down. 😂

I keep having these "random strokes of genius", where I solve problems I have been struggling to find solutions to, with ease. I find myself continuously wondering if this is how it's supposed to be? If this is how "normal" people function?
Also, I can apparently read pretty fast AND comprehend it without having to reread it 6 times?
And, it seems my coordination has improved, along with all of my senses?? Everything seems brighter and more detailed.

Other weird things I've noticed that may or may not be related:
- No more carb cravings
- No more shortness of breath
- Less Fibromayalgia symptoms
- Less getting up at night to go potty
- Drinking more water

Honestly, I can't believe all the things I have been able to accomplish this week. The ablity to decide what you want to think about and focus on instead of chaos seeping out of your ears and forcing itself upon you is amazing. Truly.
So, treating my ADHD has caused me to thoroughly purge my home of unnecessary clutter. I'm feeling very accomplished and so much lighter!

I catch the dog, everyone piles into the truck. We get home, I hop in the shower and she makes me tacos. I never thought I would have been the obe having an accident at the vet today.

"Remember the twerking Miley Cyrus cat? That's where I am. Please!"
Daughter comes around the corner and the dogs spot her. One breaks free from her collar so I am now chasing her through the parking lot in my wet pants while everyone watches, but I have been rescued!

"Honey? Listen to Momma closely... I need you to back the truck that you hate to drive out of the garage and come pick me up."
"Mom! No! Don't make me!"
"Please. I peed my pants and am stranded at the vet!"
"No, please! Ugh, I don't even know where that is!"

Great! The dogs are coming back out! I can finally head back home! I usher them into the car, put on my seatbelt and pushed the ignition button. Click. Nothing. Click, click, click. Nothing. OMG. Who am I going to call to pick me up in my wet pants on a Tuesday morning?

Holding it. Holding it. Holding it. Oh no. Queue the huge stash of emergency restaurant napkins in the glove box. Seat is protected, but pants are wet. Honestly, once the twitchy muscles start, I wouldn't have made it to the bathroom anyway.
Nobody is allowed inside the building, and there are now other buildings around that I could run to to go potty, nor am I supposed to leave because dogs are inside.

I sent them in to their appointment and had planned to sit in the car and read. Fibromyalgia had different ideas. Twitchy muscles are one of my most common symptoms. Today, it was my bladder that decided to start twerking.
So, embarrassing story about my ordeal of a day. It all began this morning. A trip to the vet with my dogs for a check up...
